doc.ContractDescription: GAMMA RAY BURSTS (GRB) ARE AMONG THE MOST EXTREME AND EXCITING OBJECTS IN ASTROPHYSICS. MAJOR ADVANCES IN OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THESE SOURCES IN THE LAST DECADE HAS BEEN POSSIBLE THROUGH MISSIONS SUCH AS SWIFT AND FERMI. HOWEVER, THESE FACILITIES HAVE ALSO OPENED A NUMBER OF PUZZLING QUESTIONS ABOUT THE PHYSICAL ORIGIN AND NATURE OF THE GRB PROMPT RADIATION, AND HOW THESE RELATE TO THE HIGHER ENERGY GEV EMISSION, THE TIME DELAYS BETWEEN THE VARIOUS ENERGY BANDS, THE SPECTRUM AND THE RADIATIVE EFFICIENCY. WE PLAN TO CALCULATE NEXT GENERATION MODELS OF GAMMA RAY BURST SOURCES WHICH ADDRESS RECENT FERMI AND SWIFT OBSERVATIONS, AND WHICH TAKE INTO ACCOUNT NEW THEORETICAL DEVELOPMENTS, INCLUDING THE POSSIBLE ROLE OF MAGNETIC FIELDS ON THE DYNAMICS, THE EFFECT OF PHOTOSPHERIC RADIATION IN THE PROMPT EMISSION, AND THE POSSIBLE ROLE OF HADRONIC PROCESSES IN ADDITION TO CONVENTIONAL LEPTONIC PROCESSES. WE WILL USE BOTH SEMI-ANALYTICAL TOOLS AND EXTENSIVE MONTE CARLO MULTI-ZONE SIMULATIONS TO INVESTIGATE THE DETAILED TIME-DEPENDENT SPECTRAL EVOLUTION OF BURSTS EXTENDING FROM THE OPTICAL/X-RAY INTO THE GEV RANGE, AND WILL PERFORM DETAILED STATISTICAL FITS TO THE TIME-BINNED SPECTRAL DATA OF FERMI AND SWIFT.
